Now, after, let's say now, we're talking about

09:14.842 --> 09:20.212
1952, right? Is that about when you leave the 
plant? We shut down the plant in 1952. I left in 1952

09:24.780 --> 09:27.966
to go overseas. The plant was shut down July 1, 
1953, and I'm still over there. I came back in

09:32.734 --> 09:35.179
September of that year. And then what do you do? 
Then you come back to work here? I came back to work

09:38.572 --> 09:41.277
here and finished up the plant here. Okay. And then 
we moved out there in 1954. Yeah. So I was still

09:46.345 --> 09:50.412
working on the engineering and construction of 
this plant when I came back. And then you consult

09:50.932 --> 09:53.757
for private industry then? Then? No, I couldn't. I 
worked for the Bureau. So you don't begin to

09:57.663 --> 10:00.448
consult for Diamond Shamrock then until after? I 
never consulted for Diamond Shamrock. I just

10:01.830 --> 10:03.012
happened to be interested in their Oh, OK. And the 
fact that they've got a plant here. And I've always

10:06.276 --> 10:10.761
been interested in these metallurgical 
processes. And the thing I found out was that they

10:11.461 --> 10:18.489
were having, I understand, having some trouble 
getting natural gas. And I thought that there was

10:18.549 --> 10:27.378
some talk, and again, this is forehand, that they 
might move the whole operation over here at

10:18.549 --> 10:27.378
Kingwood. And I was interested in that, if indeed I 
could help. That's the two-stage hydrogenation.

10:33.012 --> 10:39.500
I'm not really too sure about it, exactly how they 
do it. I think the hydrogenation work was done over

10:40.141 --> 10:50.654
in Maryland, and then the product was shipped 
here, and I think it was an electric furnace the

10:40.141 --> 10:50.654
rest of the way, but I'm not 100 percent sure. The 
only thing I'm interested in, what was

10:52.997 --> 10:59.745
interesting, was making hydrogen from coal 
natural gas. I worked for the guy that developed

11:01.223 --> 11:04.307
the natural gas reforming, Shapley.

11:07.571 --> 11:10.234
But now it's—we've got to go the other way. See, 
that's one of the things. All these plants that

11:12.437 --> 11:19.626
have been built, nobody has ever faced up to making 
the hydrogen. Louisiana, Missouri, we got it from

11:19.646 --> 11:24.372
our—we call them cracking furnaces. They call 
them reformers now. And then all these other

11:26.735 --> 11:30.019
plants have been built. solvent-refined coal, 
and high gas, and all of them, they've always

11:30.640 --> 11:42.395
gotten the hydrogen from reforming natural gas, 
because it's an easy way to do it. So nobody's

11:42.415 --> 11:46.460
really faced up to it. Is this the high gas process 
that started IGT? Yeah, that's right. They've

11:50.304 --> 11:52.087
gotten away from the hydrogenation now. It's 
pretty much an oxygen process, pretty much like

11:52.107 --> 11:56.412
xanthine, really.

